.nana-lang 1.0	`

`!!
`### Banana Data Interchange and Markup Language
	a text, data-interchange language with beautification.
	many features, but intuitive and very easy to begin using.
	new lineâ€”indentationâ€”delimiter. that's all you need to know to start using.

	nearly the whole file is the data, and easy to read.
	people already understand how generic lists work from real life: new line means new item, and indentation means a descendant. the single delimiter adds all other functionality.
	this creates a low bar for entry, because you never have to worry about accidentally invoking some function you don't know. they're all trapped behind the delimiter.
	I shouldn't have to reformat my data to accomodate the file format. that's why there's one delimiter that hides all of the commands.

	think of .nana-lang as a child of YAML and Markdown. it is more efficient and intuitive than YAML, and contains visual beautification for readability and aesthetics.

`# Use it to:
	hold or transfer data, like JSON and YAML.
	rich text, like markdown.
	simple text list, like plain text.


`# How it works:
	everything is an item, which is a text object, that may have children.
	a new line means a new item.
	an indented line is a child of the closest item above it with less indentation.
	the delimiter is used to add all functionality.
	the delimiter is followed by 1 or more command characters.
	all items are trimmed of leading and trailing whitespace, and empty lines are ignored. this allows the user to control whitespace separation to their preference.
	item value assignments cascade, so the most recent value overwrites any previous value. (This is useful for default values.)
	if the version has s at the end of it, the file is in strict mode, and will notify of duplicate items.

the indentation method and delimiter are defined in the first line, after the file type declaration and version, you place your preferred indentation (tab by default) and delimiter (backtick by default).
.nana-lang 0.8s	`

`## Standard Commands
	``			backtick: the literal for the delimiter character. if you need to use the delimiter character in your text value, place backtick after it.
					NOTE: this is NOT the delimiter twice. if the delimiter is changed to something like $$, you must still use the backtick to get the literal &; e.g. $$`
	`!			a comment that continues to the End Of the Line (EOL).
	`!!			a comment block that ends with !!`. these are nestable, so commenting out a section with an existing comment block won't cause a conflict.
	`(			a raw text block. all characters are treated as text by the language until the closing )`. this allows text that has: leading or trailing whitespace, new lines, and the delimiter within it. new lines will break the flow of indentation, however.
	`((			a raw text block that starts on the next line and continues until a line that has only ))`. this block breaks the flow of indentation, but guarantees fidelity of whitespace and new lines in the text value.
	`=			notify parser that this is not text. value is trimmed. e.g. `=3.14159 or `= true or `=null
	`&			join, used at EOL. the next line (excluding its indentation) is a continuation of this line.
	`&&			same as `& but with a space separator.
	`&&&		same as `& but with a new line separator.
	`:			inserted after a parent, it allows children on the same line. (aesthetics)
	`,			inserted between items, this allows a horizontal list. (aesthetics)
	`			EOL: represents an item with no text. this is used in an array, typically to hold dictionary entries.
	`%			defaults. its children will be added initially to all subsequent siblings of this item.
	`|			tables. its children are the column names. its younger siblings are rows and their children fall into these columns.
	`[]			the brackets allow extensibility with more advanced commands.
					e.g. `[url]`(http://example.com)`
	`.nana-lang	this ends the data by itself, or allows a redefinition of the version, indentation, and delimiter if those are included.


	VISUAL ELEMENTS. These work within comments as well. They are typically ignored by parsers.
		`{		a code block. it should be rendered with a monospaced font and different background. up to closing }`
		`{{		a raw code block starting on the next line. delimiters are ignored within. up to line with just }}`
		`###	header, from 1 to 3 #. it increases font size. (inverse from markdown # functionality. more means bigger here).
		`+++	emphasis. from 1 to 3 + are used for different emphasis levels. e.g. italic, bold, and bold italic. nestable, up to the closing +++`
		`+++	used at end of an item to simply emphasize the entire item.
		`_		underline up to the closing _` or used at EOL to underline item.
		`-		strikethrough up to the closing -` or EOL.
		`-		used at end of an item to strikethrough it and its descendants. (this can be used to check off items in a list)
		`---	used on a line by itself with 1 to 3 -, it creates a horizontal line of varying thickness.
		`'		quote emphasis. formatting indicates a quote block until the closing '`. (nestable)
		`''		a raw quote block starting on next line, up until a line with ''`
		`?		review emphasis. red formatting to draw attention to errors or immediate problems.
		BULLETS. 
		`*		used at end of item. causes all children to have â€˘ bullets preceding them, or whatever character immediately follows the *.
		Numbered Lists. They can be followed by a separator character (like .) and they can increase the depth of the indentation to match the largest number with some padding.
		`*0		bullets are a 1-based numbered list.
		`*I		bullets are classic roman numerals. i.e. I II III IIII V 
		`*i		bullets are classic little roman numerlas. i.e. i ii iii iiii v
		`*A		bullets are uppercase english letters. i.e. A B C
		`*a		bullets are lowercase english letters. i.e. a b c


	Command Character Cheat Sheet:
	`!		comment
	`@		
	`#		heading
	`$		
	`%		default
	`^		
	`&		join
	`*		bullets
	`()		raw
	`[]		special commands
	`{}		code
	`-		strikethrough and line
	`_		underline
	`=		non-text
	`+		emphasis
	`\		
	`|		columns
	`/		
	`?		attention
	`.		
	`,		split
	`<>		? special. url.
	`;		
	`:		name:value
	`'		
	`"		quote (duh)
	`~		
	`		<new line> text-less item

!!`

How the data parses to arrays and dicts/hashmaps.
	if an item has no children, it's just its value.
	if an item has 1 child, it's a dict name with a value.
	if an item has multiple children, it's a dict name with an array of values.
	if an item has no text, it's an array.

`---

`# Examples

fruits
	apple
		granny smith
		fuji
	banana
	cherry
		rainier
	date

`!!
JSON equivalent:
{	
	"fruits": [
		{
			"apple": [
			"granny smith",
			"fuji"
			]
		},
		"banana",
		"cherry": "rainier",
		"date"
	]
}
!!`


users
	`
		name
			george warshington
		age
			`=53
		titles
			general
		address
			1600 Pennsylvania Ave `&&&
			Washington, D.C.
	`
		name
			rbrhrm lrncrn
		age
			`= 34
		titles
			prez`, breaker of chains`, first of his name
		quote
			four score and `&
			seven years ago

`!!
	the chidren of users have no names, so this is an ordred array.
	users[0].name = "george warshington"
	users[1].age = 34
!!`


myapp
	name`: ExampleApp
	version`: 1.0
	debug
		`=false
	ports
		8080`, 8081
		8520
	database
		host
			localhost
		port
			54321
		credentials
			user`: admin
			password`: secret
	features
		`
			name`: auth
			enabled`:`=true
		`
			name`: logging
			enabled`:`= False
	notes
		`((
Line 1
Line 2
Line 3
))`
	metadata
		`= null

stuff
	users
		`%					`! this injected into all subsequent siblings.
			theme
				light
		`
			username
				myname
			password
				mypass
			theme
				dark		`! cascading means this overwrites the initial value set in %.
		`
			username
				urname
			password
				urpass


mytable
	`|
		First Name
		Last Name
		Birth Year
	`
		Gorge
		Warshngtn
		`=1905
	`
		Brahm
		Lrncrn
		`=1987


`!!
JSON parsing:
{
	"mytable": [
		{
			"First Name": "Gorge",
			"Last Name": "Warshngtn",
			"Birth Year": 1905
		},
		{
			"First Name": "Brahm",
			"Last Name": "Lrncrn",
			"Birth Year": 1987
		}
	]
}
!!`


`# Multilines

`! standard parent-child format.
parent
	child1
	child2
	child3

`! parent with child.
parent`: child

`! horizontal list of children.
parent
	child1`, child2`, child3

`! parent with horizontal list of children.
parent`: child1`, child2`, child3

`! parent with child on multiple lines. no separator.
`! the weather is lovely
parent
	the weath`&
	er is lovely
	
`! parent with child on multiple lines. space separator.
`! the weather is lovely
parent
	the weather is`&&
	lovely

`! parent with child on multiple lines. new line separator.
`! the weather
`! is lovely
parent
	the weather`&&&
	is lovely
